name: Gene Munster
tweet: 9) iPad Pro gets juiced with M1 chip. It's official, iPad Pro is more of a Mac than an iPad. Pricing remains unchanged for 11 in. at $799, 10% price increase for 12.9 in. to $1099. Apple is embracing its premium product and higher price model that has severed it well for 20 yrs.

name: Gene Munster
tweet: 7) iMac gets an 18% starting price increase and increased display to 24 inch. Say goodbye to 21.5 inch and 27 inch iMacs. Starting at $1299, up from $1099. We estimate iMac is 2.5% of total revenue, and will grow 10% plus for the next few years from work and learn from anywhere.

name: Gene Munster
tweet: 6) the iMac gets the Zoom optimization overhaul. Better cameras, mics and speakers. Much needed for the work-from-anywhere paradigm.

name: Gene Munster
tweet: 5) New iMac M1 brings back colors. Time-tested Apple product playbook, add color to juice sales. First time iMac has added colors since its launch in 1998, a year after Jobs' return.

name: Gene Munster
tweet: 3) New Apple TV 4K has new A12 chip. Speed bump improvements along with helpful new remote that likely won’t move the demand needle. We estimate Apple TV is about 1% of total revenue and growing at 5%. Pricing is unchanged at $179 plus which means it's a high end smart TV device.

name: Gene Munster
tweet: In the end, our view is that the biggest obstacle in 2021 for shares of $AAPL would be a continued rotation out of Big Tech. Even if that happens, we expect investors to return to $AAPL given its foundational position in the future of tech.

name: Gene Munster
tweet: 7) “What do you see as the most challenging obstacle ahead for 2021?”  Cook said, “I don’t see obstacles so much as opportunities,” highlighting the degree to which the Apple teams rose to the occasion last year as an indication it's prepared to handle whatever comes its way.

name: Gene Munster
tweet: 6) “What will the impact of new stimulus measures be on the business?”  Cook took the high road and focused on the stimulus' purpose of helping people, not speculating on impact to Apple. We believe they'll receive a small but measurable benefit from consumer stimulus spending.

name: Gene Munster
tweet: 5) “Why don’t you increase your dividend more?”  Apple said they “plan annual dividend increases." We expect an increase in dividends and share buybacks when they report Mar quarter. Related: investors don’t fully appreciate positive significance of returning to net cash neutral.

name: Gene Munster
tweet: Our take is that Apple has done the best out of Big Tech in navigating the regulatory threat by making proactive changes to the App Store. While not out of the woods, they’re on track to emerge largely unscathed.

name: Gene Munster
tweet: 4) “Are you worried about regulation forcing a change to the App Store business model?”  Cook acknowledged that government scrutiny is reasonable and that “Apple doesn’t have a dominant position in any market we compete in.”

name: Gene Munster
tweet: For starters, not all acquisitions are created equal, so there are limited insights from the pace step down. That said, the takeaway is likely they feel confident they can innovate from within. We don’t see any mega acquisitions as likely over the next few years.

name: Gene Munster
tweet: 3) Regarding M&A, “are there any acquisitions in the future?”  Of course they’re not going to answer this question, yet Cook noted they made about 80 acquisitions through the 2015 and 2016 period, and from 2017-present they’ve made 17 acquisitions.

name: Gene Munster
tweet: 2) “What are the ways in which Apple is diversifying its supply chain?”  The company had little to say with the exception of reiterating its commitment to contribute $350B to the US economy. Absent was any language about diversifying supply chain away from China.
